UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'One of the most magical places on earth — and it''s right here in Northern Ireland. Around 40,000 interlocking hexagonal basalt columns stretch out along the coastline, formed by an ancient volcanic eruption over 60 million years ago. Legend has it the giant Finn McCool built the causeway to walk to Scotland, and honestly, standing here it''s easy to believe him. Otis is going to have the time of his life clambering over the stones, and the views out to sea are absolutely breathtaking. One of those places that genuinely takes your breath away every single time.' WHERE name = 'Giant''s Causeway';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'A long, winding avenue of ancient beech trees planted in the 18th century, their gnarled branches stretching and intertwining overhead to form a spectacular natural tunnel. It feels like stepping into another world entirely — mysterious, beautiful and completely unlike anything else in Ireland. You might recognise it from Game of Thrones, where it featured as the King''s Road. At its best first thing in the morning when the mist rolls in and the light filters through the branches. Free to visit, magical to experience, and impossible to forget.' WHERE name = 'The Dark Hedges';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'Belfast''s brilliant interactive science centre, sitting right on the waterfront at the Odyssey. Across four floors of hands-on exhibits, you can launch rockets, create electricity, build structures, and explore how the world works — all by touching, pressing, pulling and playing. It''s genuinely one of those places where the adults end up just as engrossed as the kids. Otis could spend an entire day here without seeing everything. Widely regarded as one of the best days out in Belfast, and it absolutely lives up to the reputation.' WHERE name = 'W5 Science Centre';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'Belfast''s national museum and it''s completely free — one of the best free attractions in the whole of Ireland. Spread across five floors, it covers everything from Irish history and the Troubles to ancient Egyptian mummies, dinosaur fossils, and a stunning collection of fine art. The natural history section alone will keep little ones wide-eyed for hours. It sits at the edge of the beautiful Botanic Gardens, so you can move between the two and make a full day of it. The kind of place you can visit again and again and always discover something new.' WHERE name = 'Ulster Museum';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'Nestled in the historic city of Armagh, this brilliant planetarium has been inspiring wonder about the night sky since 1968. The dome show takes you on a breathtaking journey through space — past planets, through star clusters and out to the edges of the known universe — all from a comfy seat looking up. There are interactive exhibits, a sensory room, a meteorite you can actually touch, and outdoor trails through the observatory grounds. The shows are designed to be accessible for all ages, and little ones tend to absolutely love the experience of lying back and watching the stars appear above them.' WHERE name = 'Armagh Planetarium';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'Right on our doorstep and one of the best-preserved Norman castles in all of Ireland. Built in 1177 by the Anglo-Norman knight John de Courcy, it has stood watch over Belfast Lough for over 800 years — surviving sieges, invasions and centuries of history. You can explore the great hall, climb the towers for stunning views over the harbour, and discover the castle''s remarkable story through exhibits inside. It''s the kind of place that makes history feel real and exciting, and for little ones there is nothing quite like standing inside a proper medieval castle and feeling the weight of all those centuries.' WHERE name = 'Carrickfergus Castle';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'A stunning 18th century estate sitting on the southern shores of Strangford Lough, owned and managed by the National Trust. The house itself is fascinatingly eccentric — one half classical, one half Gothic, because the husband and wife who built it couldn''t agree on a style. But it''s the 820 acres of grounds that make Castle Ward truly special: ancient woodland, a working Victorian farmyard, a walled garden, and a beautiful adventure play area for little ones. Game of Thrones fans will recognise it as Winterfell. The views over Strangford Lough are some of the finest in all of Ireland.' WHERE name = 'Castle Ward';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'Just east of Portrush, Whiterocks is one of the most dramatic and beautiful beaches in Northern Ireland. The beach gets its name from the striking white chalk cliffs and sea stacks that rise from the sand — carved into incredible shapes by centuries of wind and water. Rock pools hide beneath the cliffs at low tide, perfect for little explorers, while the wide expanse of golden sand stretches out in both directions as far as the eye can see. On a clear day the views across to Rathlin Island and Scotland are stunning. One of those beaches that genuinely makes you proud to be from Northern Ireland.' WHERE name = 'Whiterocks Beach';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'Two miles of golden sand stretching along the North Coast, backed by wild sand dunes and looked after by the National Trust. What makes Portstewart Strand unique in Ireland is that you can drive your car right down onto the beach — a tradition that has delighted families for generations. At low tide the flat, firm sand goes on forever, making it perfect for toddlers to run, splash and explore in complete safety. The dunes behind are a nature reserve full of wildlife, and the walks through them are beautiful. On a sunny day there is nowhere better in Northern Ireland to spend an afternoon.' WHERE name = 'Portstewart Strand';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'A hidden gem tucked away in the heart of County Tyrone. Drum Manor is a beautiful forest park with winding woodland trails, peaceful ponds where you can feed the ducks, a lovely butterfly garden, and one of the best children''s play parks in the mid-Ulster area. The forest trails are easy and well-maintained, perfect for little legs, and the whole place has a wonderfully calm and unhurried atmosphere. Pack a picnic, bring some bread for the ducks, and let the afternoon stretch out. One of those places that locals treasure and visitors are always delighted to discover.' WHERE name = 'Drum Manor Forest Park';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'Ireland''s first nature reserve, established in 1967, and one of the most strikingly beautiful stretches of coastline in the entire country. A vast system of ancient sand dunes — some over 6,000 years old — rolls down to a wide, wild beach with the Mourne Mountains rising dramatically behind. A boardwalk winds through the dunes to the shore, making it accessible even with a buggy. The beach itself is wide, flat and wonderfully safe for paddling and playing. Wildflowers cover the dunes in summer, and the whole place has a sense of timeless, unspoilt beauty that is genuinely rare.' WHERE name = 'Murlough Nature Reserve';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'One of Northern Ireland''s oldest and most beloved country parks, and conveniently close to home. Crawfordsburn packs a remarkable amount into one place — a sandy beach on Belfast Lough, a dramatic wooded glen, a stunning waterfall, and miles of easy walking trails through ancient woodland. The paths are well-maintained and largely buggy-friendly, and the visitor centre has a lovely café where you can warm up with a coffee and a scone after your walk. It''s the kind of place that works beautifully in any season — carpeted in bluebells in spring, golden in autumn, and peaceful and bracing in winter.' WHERE name = 'Crawfordsburn Country Park';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'Perched on the slopes of Cave Hill overlooking Belfast, the zoo is home to over 140 species from around the world. From spectacled bears and red pandas to giraffes, lions, gorillas and a remarkable colony of California sea lions, there is wildlife around every corner. The zoo has undergone significant investment in recent years and the enclosures are large, naturalistic and thoughtfully designed. The views over Belfast from the upper sections of the zoo are spectacular. There is also a great children''s play park on site, and the whole visit can easily fill a full day. One of Belfast''s most cherished family days out.' WHERE name = 'Belfast Zoo';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'Tucked away at the tip of the Ards Peninsula in the pretty village of Portaferry, Exploris is Northern Ireland''s only public aquarium and one of the finest in Ireland. Home to everything from sharks and rays to seahorses and octopuses, plus a wonderful seal sanctuary where rescued common and grey seals are rehabilitated before being released back into the wild. The touch tank, where you can feel the velvety skin of a ray, is an absolute highlight for little ones. Penguin feeding time draws a crowd every day. The whole visit is magical, unhurried, and educational — everything a day out should be.' WHERE name = 'Exploris Aquarium';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'The Wildfowl and Wetlands Trust centre at Castle Espie sits on the western shore of Strangford Lough and is one of the most peaceful and charming family days out in the whole of County Down. The wetland grounds are home to thousands of ducks, geese and swans — many of them so tame they will eat from your hand. In season, Castle Espie hosts internationally important flocks of pale-bellied Brent geese that migrate all the way from Arctic Canada. There is a brilliant woodland play area, a soft play barn for rainy days, a lovely café, and beautiful views across the lough. A place that soothes and delights in equal measure.' WHERE name = 'WWT Castle Espie';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'The Queen of the Glens — Glenariff is widely considered the most beautiful of the nine Glens of Antrim, and a visit to Glenariff Forest Park makes it easy to understand why. A series of spectacular waterfalls tumble through a wooded gorge, connected by well-maintained wooden walkways and bridges that feel genuinely magical to walk through. The waterfall trail is the most accessible route and perfect for toddlers, with the sound of rushing water and the dappled green light filtering through the forest canopy creating an atmosphere unlike anywhere else in Ireland. There is a lovely café at the entrance for afterwards. A place of real, quiet wonder.' WHERE name = 'Glenariff Forest Park';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'Hidden away in the quiet village of Seaforde in County Down, this is one of those genuinely special places that feels like a discovery. The walled garden is one of the finest in Ireland — immaculately kept, wonderfully peaceful, and full of rare plants and trees. But the real highlight, especially for little ones, is the tropical butterfly house: a warm, lush enclosure filled with hundreds of exotic butterflies from around the world, flying freely all around you. They land on your hands, your shoulders, your hair. Peacocks roam the gardens freely. The whole experience is enchanting, gentle and completely magical. Otis is going to love every second.' WHERE name = 'Seaforde Butterfly House';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'Just outside Newtownards on the Bangor Road, the Ark Open Farm has built a remarkable reputation as one of the very best family days out in Northern Ireland — and one visit makes it immediately clear why. The farm is home to a wonderful variety of animals: rare breed pigs, goats, donkeys, alpacas, reptiles, and so much more, all of which you can get genuinely hands-on with. The staff are knowledgeable, warm and brilliant with children, taking the time to introduce every animal and answer every question. The café is outstanding. The play areas are excellent. It is one of those places where you arrive for an hour and stay for the whole day.' WHERE name = 'Ark Open Farm';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'A family-run working farm in Dundonald that has been welcoming visitors for decades, and there is a warmth and authenticity to Streamvale that is hard to find anywhere else. Watch the sheepdog trials as the border collies round up the flock with extraordinary precision. Take the tractor ride out through the fields to see the deer herd and the Jacob''s sheep. Feed the lambs, hold the chicks, and get up close to Highland cattle, pigs, horses and goats. The whole experience is wonderfully hands-on and genuinely educational, with passionate staff who clearly love what they do. Otis'' absolute favourite — and it''s not hard to see why.' WHERE name = 'Streamvale Open Farm';
UPDATE public.places SET long_description = 'Northern Ireland''s largest indoor play centre, located just off the M2 in Belfast, and on a rainy afternoon it is an absolute lifesaver. Across multiple levels there are soft play frames, ball pools, slides, a zip wire, climbing walls and activity zones designed for different age groups — including a dedicated toddler area with age-appropriate equipment for the smallest visitors. It is the kind of place where children burn off every last bit of energy in the best possible way. The café serves decent food and good coffee, which is exactly what you need when you''re watching a small person throw themselves around for two hours. Brilliant, chaotic, and absolutely worth it.' WHERE name = 'Play Factore';